257-259 Bleecker Street, at and adjoining the N. E. corner of Cornelia Street, showing two 3½ story buildings at this location.

To the rear of the corner structure is a 1 story shed and a three story brick building, No. 35 Cornelia Street.

At the right margin appears a portion of a brick faced frame building (No. 255) standing at the S.E. corner. Note the gas lamp in front of same.

J. J. Corell
P. L. Sperr

1900

(1)
255 Bleecker Street at the S.E. corner of Cornelia Street. The house is also called 42 Cornelia Street.
February, 1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

(2)
The same, showing also 253-247 Bleecker Street, the same frame house, with its neighbors. The four brick houses shown adjoining and south of it were formerly all the same type of brick house, with dormer window, that No. 249 still is; but since 1922 the other three have been rebuilt.
April, 1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

Cornelia Street, east of, adjoining, and at the N.E. corner of Bleeker Street.
May 1, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

Bleecker Street, north from Cornelia Street, showing a pushcart market located here. This extends to Jones St. View No. 2 is limited to structures numbered 271 to 265. These are the four low buildings appearing in the mid-ground of the preceding photograph. The vantage point is Morton (originally Ardens) Street which terminates here.
